{"id":2113732,"title":"Optimal Scaling of Mala for Nonlinear Regression","authors":["Laird Arnault Breyer","Mauro Piccioni","Sergio Scarlatti"],"_abstract":"ABSTRACT We address the problem of simulating efficiently from the posterior distribution over the parameters of a particular class of nonlinear regression models using a Langevin-Metropolis sampler. It is shown that as the number N of parameters increases, the proposal variance must scale as N{-1/3} in order to converge to a diffusion. This generalizes previous results of Roberts and Rosenthal [J. R. Stat. Soc. Ser. B Stat. Methodol. 60 (1998) 255-268] for the i.i.d. case, showing the robustness of their analysis.","cited_in":[{"id":233967527,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233967527_Optimal_scaling_for_the_transient_phase_of_Metropolis_Hastings_algorithms_The_longtime_behavior"},{"id":232718818,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232718818_Optimal_scaling_for_the_transient_phase_of_the_random_walk_Metropolis_algorithm_The_mean-field_limit"},{"id":232276216,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232276216_Optimal_scaling_of_random_walk_Metropolis_algorithms_with_discontinuoustarget_densities"},{"id":222298844,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/222298844_Optimal_acceptance_rates_for_Metropolis_algorithms_Movin_beyond_0234"},{"id":1771219,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/1771219_Bedard_M_Weak_convergence_of_metropolis_algorithms_for_non-iid_target_distributions_Ann_Appl_Probab_17_1222-1244"},{"id":277289463,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/277289463_Optimal_scaling_of_Metropolis_algorithms_is_0234_as_robust_as_believed"},{"id":24111924,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/24111924_An_Adaptive_Version_for_the_Metropolis_Adjusted_Langevin_Algorithm_with_a_Truncated_Drift"},{"id":227719006,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/227719006_Optimal_scaling_of_Metropolis_algorithms_Heading_toward_general_target_distributi